'''''Exxon Corp. v. Exxon Insurance Consultants International Ltd''''' [[Case citation|[1982] Ch. 119]] is a leading decision in [[English law]] on the existence of [[copyright]] in a name alone and the infringement of a [[trade mark]]. The Court found that typically there is no copyright in a name, invented or otherwise, and that a trade mark can only be infringed when there the infringing party shares part of the market segment.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}

==Trade mark==
With regard to the trade mark, the Court found that the use of this word by the defendants, who work in a field that in no way shares a [[Market (economics)|market]] segment with the plaintiff, in no way dilutes the plaintiff's brand name nor infringes on its trade mark.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}}

